    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Describes the style of a group of young painters who met at the  Académie Julian in the fall of 1888 to form a brotherhood called the “Nabis,” a Hebrew word meaning “prophets.” The group was spearheaded by Paul Sérusier. Nabi paintings often feature textured surfaces created by varied brushstrokes, and avoided the illusion of depth.</Note_Text>
